(10770, 109, 'http://www.americanbar.org/', 'Janet Spragens Pro Bono Award', NULL, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/government_public/awards/hodson_award.html', ' Indigent', 0, '2015-04-13', 11, 'This award was established in 2002 to recognize one or more individuals or law firms for outstanding and sustained achievements in pro bono activities in the tax law.  In 2007 the award was renamed in honor of the late Janet Spragens, who received the award in 2006 in recognition of her dedication to the development of low income taxpayer clinics throughout the United States.\nThe criteria for selection of an individual recipient of the award are:  (i) the individual be a tax lawyer, whether living or deceased; (ii) the individual is or was a member of the Section of Taxation; and (iii) the individual has, through years of service, demonstrated an ongoing commitment to pro bono activities, particularly in the area of Federal and state taxation.', 1, 1, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2016-03-16 12:45:21'),
(10771, 109, 'http://www.americanbar.org/aba.html', 'Outstanding Young Military Service Lawyer Award', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/government_public/awards/nelson_award.html', '', 0, '2015-04-13', 11, 'This award, a joint effort of the American Bar Association Young Lawyer Division and Judge Advocate Association, recognizes the legal contributions of one young judge advocate from each uniformed service: the U.S. Army, U.S. Navy, U.S. Air Force, U.S. Marine Corps, and U.S. Coast Guard.  Every judge advocate command is encouraged to nominate one young officer under the conditions herein. As of August.  Nominations will be reviewed by an award panel within the JAA who will \nname the awardees for each Service.\nNominations will be evaluated based on a narrative description of professional accomplishments, service to the community, leadership, and development of subordinates. Online submission: http://www.americanbar.org/groups/young_lawyers/awards_scholarships/outstanding_young_military_service_lawyer_award.html', 0, 1, 'Individual; Organization', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3796, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10772, 109, 'http://www.americanbar.org/', 'Child Advocacy Award (Young Lawyer)', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/young_lawyers/awards_scholarships/child_advocacy_award.html', 'Child Advocacy', 0, '2015-04-30', 11, 'Each year in conjunction with the Center on Children and the Law, the ABA Young Lawyers Division honors one young lawyer and one non-young lawyer for dedicated service on behalf of children. Award recipients are recognized at the Young Lawyers Division Assembly during the ABA Annual Meeting\nAny lawyer or judge involved in child advocacy is eligible. The award is given based on an individual''s personal achievement and commitment. It is not given to groups of people, organizations, or posthumously. Previous nominees not selected may be re-nominated. Young Lawyer (on September 1 the individual must be less than 36 years of age or admitted to practice in his/her first bar within the past five years)\nNomination packet. The packet includes:\nA completed online nomination form.\nSupporting documentation which needs to emailed to be as one single document in either a PDF or Microsoft Word format. The submission must be 10 pages or less. Faxes will not be accepted. Supporting documentation should include:\nA nomination letter from nominator explaining the qualifications of the nominee and setting forth the reasons why the nominee should be awarded the Child Advocacy Award.\nThe nominee’s biographical resume, including an explanation of the nominee’s legal service on the behalf of children, employment and professional history.\nUp to three letters of recommendation. Examples include letters from the nominee’s clients, individuals familiar with the nominee’s service on behalf of children, the nominee’s current or former employers, fellow practitioners, or any other individual who can explain why the nominee should be receive the Child Advocacy Award.', 0, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3797, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10773, 109, 'http://www.americanbar.org/aba.html', 'Award of Excellence in Environmental, Energy and Resources Stewardship Award', 2015, 'https://www.justice.org/what-we-do/enhance-practice-law/professional-recognition-awards-scholarship/awards/association-1', '', 0, '2015-06-30', 11, 'This award was established in 2002 to recognize and honor the accomplishments of a person, organization, or group that has distinguished itself in environmental, energy, and resources stewardship.\nWhile nominees are likely to be a lawyer and/or law related organizations, this is not a requirement for nomination. Nominees may be lawyers, industry managers, public officials, non-government organization members, policy analysts, educators, or any other person who has demonstrated significant achievement or leadership or organizations that have demonstrated similar significant achievement or leadership. Persons and organizations active in sustainable development, environmental, energy, and resources stewardship, and environmental, energy, and resources law in the United States and abroad may submit nominations. Self-nominations will not be accepted. Current Section Council members and officers and ABA staff are not eligible for the award.\nNomination Form - nominee and nominator names, addresses, firm/company, telephone number, fax number, and e-mail address;\nNominee’s Resume/Biography - nominee’s resume or similar summary document detailing the candidate’s or organization’s professional and volunteer accomplishments;\nNomination Narrative - a description of the specific accomplishment(s) that demonstrate significant achievement for which the nominee is being nominated and the time frame;\nSupporting Material - supporting documents of no more than 25 pages (excluding published articles), such as published articles by the nominee or organization, copies of media coverage of the accomplishments, proofs of past public recognition, or other materials that directly support the nomination;\nLetters of Support - minimum of three letters of support from other individuals who can attest personally to the accomplishments for which the candidate or organization is nominated; and\nNominator Statement - the nominator also must explain his or her familiarity with the nominee or organization and the accomplishments in question and provide brief biographical information about the nominator.  MAIL NOMINATION PACKAGES TO:\nABA Section of Environment, Energy, and Resources, ABA Award for Excellence in Environmental, Energy, and Resources Stewardship, 321 N. Clark St., Chicago, IL 60654', 0, 0, 'Individual; Practice group; Law Firm; Judge; Company; Legal Department; Organization', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3798, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10774, 109, 'http://www.americanbar.org/', 'Child Advocacy Award (Non-Young Lawyer)', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/environment_energy_resources/awards/stewardship_award.html', 'Child Advocacy', 0, '2015-06-30', 11, 'Each year in conjunction with the Center on Children and the Law, the ABA Young Lawyers Division honors one young lawyer and one non-young lawyer for dedicated service on behalf of children. Award recipients are recognized at the Young Lawyers Division Assembly during the ABA Annual Meeting\nAny lawyer or judge involved in child advocacy is eligible. The award is given based on an individual''s personal achievement and commitment. It is not given to groups of people, organizations, or posthumously. Previous nominees not selected may be re-nominated. Non-Young Lawyer (on September 1 the individual must be 36 or more years of age or admitted to practice in his/her first bar more than five years ago)\nNomination packet. The packet includes:\nA completed online nomination form.\nSupporting documentation which needs to emailed to be as one single document in either a PDF or Microsoft Word format. The submission must be 10 pages or less. Faxes will not be accepted. Supporting documentation should include:\nA nomination letter from nominator explaining the qualifications of the nominee and setting forth the reasons why the nominee should be awarded the Child Advocacy Award.\nThe nominee’s biographical resume, including an explanation of the nominee’s legal service on the behalf of children, employment and professional history.\nUp to three letters of recommendation. Examples include letters from the nominee’s clients, individuals familiar with the nominee’s service on behalf of children, the nominee’s current or former employers, fellow practitioners, or any other individual who can explain why the nominee should be receive the Child Advocacy Award.', 0, 1, 'Individual; Judge', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3799, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10775, 109, 'http://www.americanbar.org/aba.html', 'Government Attorney of the Year Award', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/labor_law/awards/frances_perkins_award.html', 'Government', 0, '2015-07-06', 11, 'Award will recognize exceptional achievement by federal, state, tribal, or local government attorneys who have worked or are working in the field of environment, energy, or natural resources and are esteemed by their peers and viewed as having consistently achieved distinction in an exemplary way.\nNominees are likely to be currently serving, or recently retired, career attorneys for federal, state, tribal, or local governmental entities. Self-nominations will be accepted. Current Section Council members, officers, and ABA staff of the Section are not eligible for the award.\nNomination Form – nominee and nominator names, addresses, firm/organization, telephone number, and e-mail address\nNominee’s Resume/Biography – nominee’s resume or similar summary document detailing the candidate’s professional and volunteer accomplishments during the nominee’s career\nNomination Narrative – a description of the specific accomplishment(s) that demonstrate significant achievement for which the nominee is being nominated and the time frame\nSupporting Material – supporting documents of no more than 25 pages (exclusive of published articles written by the nominee; citations to same are acceptable and preferred), such as copies of media coverage of the accomplishments, proofs of past public recognition, or other materials that directly support the nomination\nLetters of support – minimum of three letters of support from other individuals who can attest personally to the accomplishments for which the candidate is nominated\nNominator Statement – the nominator also must explain his or her familiarity with the nominee and the accomplishments in question and provide brief biographical information about the nominator.  Please e-mail your completed nominations, including the nomination form and accompanying materials. If submitting hard copies, send the original and one copy. Please use paper clips or binder clips (no staples or binding).', 0, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3800, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10776, 110, ' ', 'National Public Service Award', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/young_lawyers/awards_scholarships/national_outstanding_young_lawyer_award.html', 'Disadvantaged', 0, '2015-08-31', 11, 'The Section initiated the National Public Service Award in 1994 as part of its pro bono efforts. The National Public Service Award recognizes significant pro bono legal services that demonstrate a commitment to providing services to the poor in a business context, and recognizes the achievements resulting from the public service work for the clients and the client groups represented. Each year, the Section recognizes the pro bono efforts of an individual business lawyer, a law firm and/or a corporate law department. Award recipients have demonstrated dedication to the development or delivery of pro bono business legal services, contributed significant work toward developing innovative approaches to the delivery of pro bono business legal services, and/or provided sustained pro bono business legal counsel to nonprofit organizations or to microbusinesses in aid of community development.\nAward recipients have demonstrated dedication to the development or delivery of pro bono business legal services, contributed significant work toward developing innovative approaches to the delivery of pro bono business legal services, and/or provided sustained pro bono business legal counsel to nonprofit organizations or to microbusinesses in aid of community development.\nTo nominate a law firm, corporate legal department or individual that has provided significant pro bono legal services to the poor in a business context for the 2015 National Public Service Award:\n\nDownload the 2015 National Public Service Award Nomination Form\nEmail the completed form to Leslie Archer at leslie.archer@americanbar.org ', 0, 1, 'Individual; Law Firm; Legal Department', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3801, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10777, 111, ' ', 'Making a Difference by Breaking Barriers', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/gpsolo/awards.html', '', 0, '2015-07-31', 11, 'Making a Difference by Breaking Barriers – This award honors an attorney living or deceased who broke barriers for gender, color, disabilities or sexual orientation.\nNA', 0, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3802, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10778, 111, ' ', 'Making a Difference through Community Service', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/gpsolo/awards.html', '', 0, '2015-07-31', 11, 'Making a Difference through Community Service – This award honors an attorney living or deceased who made a significant lifetime contribution to the local community through community service.  (Not necessarily through bar work or pro bono work per se).\nNA', 0, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3803, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10779, 111, ' ', 'Making a Difference through Pro Bono Work', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/gpsolo/awards.html', 'Disadvantaged; Indigent', 0, '2015-07-31', 11, 'Making a Difference through Pro Bono Work – This award honors an attorney, law firm, corporate legal department, government attorney office or institution in the legal profession that has made an outstanding commitment to volunteer legal services for the poor and disadvantaged. (Recognizes an outstanding local attorney or group that does pro bono work).\nNA', 0, 1, 'Individual; Practice group; Law Firm; Judge; Company; Legal Department; Organization', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3804, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10780, 111, ' ', 'Making a Difference through Service to the Profession', 2015, 'http://www.americanbar.org/groups/gpsolo/awards.html', '', 0, '2015-07-31', 11, 'Making a Difference through Service to the Profession – This award honors an attorney living or deceased who made a significant contribution to the legal profession through service to the profession.  (i.e. frequent activities in bar associations, committees and services).\nNA', 0, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3805, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10781, 112, '', 'Asia Legal Awards', 2016, '', '', 0, '2016-01-11', 0, 'ALM, publisher of The American Lawyer, Corporate Counsel and Law.com and the world’s pre-eminent legal media group, is delighted to announce the ASIA LEGAL AWARDS 2016. \nCulminating in a gala dinner at Hong Kong’s Four Seasons on February 23rd, over 200 guests from the world’s leading law firms, General Counsel from the world’s leading companies, and honored guests from across the Asian legal spectrum will assemble to celebrate excellence and achievement across the region. \n\nBuilding on our established Asian publications and conferences, we will pore over submissions from over 100 law firms. The experienced and celebrated editorial staff of The American Lawyer and sister publications The Asian Lawyer and China Law & Practice will draw up a shortlist in a number of key practice areas and disciplines in both transactions and disputes. We will identify the stand-out achievements of the past 12 months, celebrate those successes, and publish a review of these flagship awards to our vast domestic U.S. readership as well as our readers right across the Asia-Pacific region.', 0, 1, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3806, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10782, 113, '', 'White Collar Crime Trailblazers', 2015, 'http://pages.email.alm.com/WhiteCollarCrimeTrailblazers/', '', 0, '2015-10-02', 11, 'For these awards, we are looking for vision, perseverance, and a steady hand guiding the technology development. In all categories, the entries should a) identify the problem/challenge/opportunity; b) explain the process of resolving the issue; c) document how the technology helped accomplish the goals, and d) detail future related plans.\n''Anyone can nominate a candidate — nominators need not work at the organization. There is no fee to enter.\n\nNote: We only accept nominations via email.\nThe competition will be judged by independent jurors. ', 1, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3807, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10783, 114, 'http://www.legalbusinessonline.com/asia', 'SE Asia Law Awards: TMT In-House Team of the Year ', 2015, 'http://www.legalbusinessonline.com/awards/se-asia-law-awards-2015', 'TMT; Technology;', 0, '2015-04-06', 8, 'The award recognizes the excellence and outstanding achievements of SE Asia''s leading law firms and in-house legal teams as well as the top deals and dealmakers.\nAll in-house teams based in SE Asia are qualified. Criteria: Complexity - the degree to which the work requires intricate legal principles or advance techniques and structures. Innovation/improvement - the degree to which the work involved original or improved techniques and structures or innovative legal rules or regulations. Breadth - the degree to which the work spanned different jurisdictions, practice areas, parties and industries. Impact/significance - the degree by which the stakeholders/bench and bar/community at large is affected.\nAll in-house teams based in SE Asia are qualified.\nAll nominations must be written in the ALB nomination form. The same must be submitted on or before the submission deadline. Work includes any transactions/deals/projects completed, cases handled, disputes settled and other legal services provided within the organisation or otherwise. Entries to any category must have been completed or provided in the previous year. Documents supplementary to the information provided in the nomination form may be submitted within the nomination period. No supplementary information will be accepted after the nomination deadline. Clients or contact persons provided in the nomination form will be contacted by ALB, as may be necessary, without prior notice to the nominating organization. It is advisable that only the names of clients whose consent for this purpose has been obtained are listed in the nomination form.\nThe judging panel consists of the general panel and the special expertise panel. It is composed of approximately 40 reputable members from the legal academe, in-house teams, law firms, legal associations or business leagues, whose identities are kept confidential prior to the awarding ceremony. The panel of judges is given one week to evaluate the accomplishments of nominees based on a research summary provided by ALB. The judges select the top three finalists for every category. A score allocated by a judge to a finalist with which or with whom he has an apparent conflict of interest is considered void. The scores given by judges to finalists are aggregated. The finalist in every category who obtains the highest score wins.', 0, 1, 'Individual; Practice group; Law Firm; Judge; Legal Department', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3808, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10784, 115, 'http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/', 'Corporate Counsel Awards', 2015, 'http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/nomination/72931', 'General Counsel; GC; In house; ', 0, '2015-04-08', 3, 'Honor the best and the brightest in-house counsel!\nAtlanta Business Chronicle and the Georgia Chapter of the Association of Corporate Counsel present the second annual Corporate Counsel Awards. This awards luncheon highlights the outstanding work by both generalists and specialists in public and private companies and nonprofit t organizations of all sizes. And, even more important, emphasizes the value these professionals add to their organizations’ bottom lines. With the legal and regulatory landscapes of many industries seeing rapid and constant evolution and change over the last several years, the role of in-house counsel has never been more crucial to each company’s success. Be with us when we honor the best and the brightest in-house counsel!\n\nThe 2014 Corporate Counsel Awards winners will be profiled in the May 2, 2014, issue of Atlanta Business Chronicle.\nQUALIFICATIONS - Nominees must:\n• Be employed as a lawyer by a company,\n• Be based in Georgia.\n• Have at least one year in the nominated position or role, and with the same company, and\n\n• Be a member of the Association of Corporate Counsel Georgia Chapter as of March 14, 2014.\n\nActive participation in ACC will be a factor in judging the awards, but is not a requirement.\nVia online form http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/nomination/64901\nThe nomination form is the chief criteria used in judging the awards.  Your nomination should address each of these qualifications, as well as the specific criteria for the award category.  If requested information or specific qualifications are omitted, your nominee may be disadvantaged in the judging process.', 0, 0, 'Individual; Practice group; Law Firm; Legal Department', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3809, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10785, 115, 'http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/', 'Atlanta''s Best Places to Work', 2016, 'http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/nomination/75692#eligibility', '', 0, '2016-07-01', 3, 'Atlanta Business Chronicle is looking for the metro area''s 2016 Best Places To Work! If your company is one of the best places to work in Atlanta, this is your chance to be recognized and let others know. \n\nAtlanta Business Chronicle, in conjunction with Quantum Workplace (www.quantumworkplace.com), will accept company nominations through July 1, 2016. Companies nominate themselves; ONLY ONE NOMINATION PER COMPANY IS NECESSARY.\n\nOnly companies with at least 10 employees can participate. Each nominated company will be contacted by Quantum and asked to participate in a scientifically valid survey conducted July through early August, 2016. Companies will then be rated based on survey responses on work environment, people practices and other matrices. Please encourage all your employees to take Quantum''s survey.', 0, 0, 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3810, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10786, 116, 'http://www.bizjournals.com/austin/', 'Best CEO', 2015, 'http://www.bizjournals.com/austin/nomination/72401', '', 0, '2015-07-31', 3, 'Nominate your Central Texas CEO! The Best CEO owns his or her company or is the company''s top executive officer. He or she lives and works in Travis, Williamson, Hays, Burnet, Caldwell or Bastrop county.\n\nEligibility Requirements\n\nThe Best CEO owns his or her company or is the company’s top executive officer. He or she lives and works in Travis, Williamson, Hays, Burnet or Bastrop county. The organization can be for-profit or nonprofit, but it must have a proven track record and be headquartered in Central Texas.\n\nThe nominee must have a strong record of innovation and outstanding performance. Extra consideration will be given to those who have had a significant career accomplishment within the past 12 months.\n\nHis or her sphere of influence should extend beyond the scope of the nominee’s career, such as a  contribution to his or her industry and/or a leadership role in the philanthropic, civic or political arenas.\n\nNominations will be accepted for CEOs in four categories based on their organization’s type and size:\n\n? Small Company CEO- 2014 revenue under $10 million\n? Medium Company CEO-2014 revenue $10 to $50 million\n? Large Company CEO- 2014 revenue over $50 million\n? Nonprofit CEO', 0, 0, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10787, 117, 'http://www.bestlawyers.com/', 'Best Lawyers in Spain', 2015, 'http://www.bestlawyers.com/About/CountryLists.aspx', '', 0, '2015-04-08', 10, 'Best Lawyers is the oldest and most respected peer-review publication in the legal profession. A listing in Best Lawyers is widely regarded by both clients and legal professionals as a significant honor, conferred on a lawyer by his or her peers. Our lists of outstanding attorneys are compiled by conducting exhaustive peer-review surveys in which tens of thousands of leading lawyers confidentially evaluate their professional peers. If the votes for an attorney are positive enough for inclusion in Best Lawyers, that attorney must maintain those votes in subsequent polls to remain on the list for each edition. Lawyers are not permitted to pay any fee to participate in or be included on our lists.\nOnline: https://www.bestlawyers.com/Admin/Nomination.aspx', 1, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3811, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10788, 117, 'http://www.bestlawyers.com/', 'Best Lawyers in America', 2015, '', '', 0, '2015-04-10', 11, 'Best Lawyers is the oldest and most respected peer-review publication in the legal profession. A listing in Best Lawyers is widely regarded by both clients and legal professionals as a significant honor, conferred on a lawyer by his or her peers. For more than three decades, Best Lawyers lists have earned the respect of the profession, the media, and the public, as the most reliable, unbiased source of legal referrals anywhere. \nOnline: https://www.bestlawyers.com/Admin/Nomination.aspx\nFor the 2014 (20th) Edition of The Best Lawyers in America, 637 lawyers in the Connecticut region listed in Best Lawyers were contacted by telephone, email, and/or fax. Each one received a ballot tailored to his or her legal specialty and location. Of that group, 489 ballots were returned (77%). The total pool of candidates included 647 previously-listed Connecticut lawyers and 437 new nominees. Overall, 49,308 votes were cast.', 1, 1, 'Individual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
