and Gas covers all upstream and downstream work including exploration, infrastructure and pipeline developments and service contracts, royalties, licensing and operation agreements. It also includes corporate issues such as M&A, capital raisings, taxation and regulatory compliance.\nRenewables focuses on the financing, development and regulatory issues surrounding wind and wave power generation, solar, biomass and geothermal energy generation. It also includes advice on compliance with clean energy regulations.\nNuclear include licensing and operation, commercial transactions, reactor oversight, enforcement and compliance, whistleblower statutes and non-retaliation policy, as well as nuclear waste and fuel procurement.\n\nNatural Resources focuses on mining and minerals exploration, development and production agreements, including royalty issues, project finance, taxation and other financing arrangements. Engineering, processing and refining contracts, sales structures and environmental issues are also covered.', '1-Dec-15', 1, 1, '', '', 'Guatemala', 'North America', 'Energy & Natural Resources', '', 'Annual', 'Carlota GarciaPatel', '', '4420 7778 1643', 'Law Firm; Practice Group', '', '', 'http://www.chambersandpartners.com/global-practice-area-definitions', 'http://www.chambersandpartners.com/', ''),
(595, 'Chambers & Partners ', 'Intellectual Property', 2015, 'The Chambers Guides have been ranking the best law firms and lawyers since 1990, and now cover 185 jurisdictions throughout the world.Intellectual Property covers disputes related to patent, copyright and trademark infringement. Litigation concerning trade secrets also features. We also feature related issues such as licensing and IP commercialisation (US patent prosecution).', '1-Dec-15', 1, 1, '', '', 'Guatemala', 'North America', 'Intellectual Property', '', 'Annual', 'Carlota GarciaPatel', '', '4420 7778 1643', 'Law Firm; Practice Group', '', '', 'http://www.chambersandpartners.com/global-practice-area-definitions', 'http://www.chambersandpartners.com/', ''),
(596, 'Chambers & Partners ', 'Life Sciences', 2016, 'The Chambers Guides have been ranking the best law firms and lawyers since 1990, and now cover 185 jurisdictions throughout the world.Life Sciences focuses on the commercialisation of life sciences products (pharmaceuticals, medical devices and biotechnology programs etc). IP issues dominate as large pharmaceuticals seek to obtain innovative, impending blockbuster drugs from biotechs and other pharmaceutical companies. Also includes the licensing and acquisition of new products from other sources (often smaller biotechs to larger suppliers). This chapter includes advice on FDA issues and the increased focus on drug and device safety, which also appears in our Healthcare and Life Sciences coverage.', '1-Jul-16', 1, 1, '', '', '', 'Asia', 'Life Sciences', '', 'Annual', '', '', '', 'Law Firm; Practice Group', '', '', 'http://www.chambersandpartners.com/global-practice-area-definitions', 'http://www.chambersandpartners.com/', ''),
(597, 'Chambers & Partners', 'Intellectual Property', 2015, 'The Chambers Guides have been ranking the best law firms and lawyers since 1990, and now cover 185 jurisdictions throughout the world.Intellectual Property covers disputes related to patent, copyright and trademark infringement. Litigation concerning trade secrets also features. We also feature related issues such as licensing and IP commercialisation (US patent prosecution).', '1-Dec-15', 1, 1, '', '', 'Cuba', 'North America', 'Intellectual Property', '', 'Annual', 'Rhodri Holtham', 'rhodri.holtham@chambersandpartners.co.uk', '4420 7778 1462', 'Law Firm; Practice Group', '', '', '', '', ''),
(598, 'Charlotte Business Journal', 'Best Places to Work', 2015, 'The Charlotte Business Journal''s Best Places to Work Awards program recognizes outstanding companies whose benefits, policies and practices are among the best in the region. Your company must have been in business for at least two years.  The company must have 10 or more employees. Company must be located in the Charlotte region. Charlotte region is defined by the following counties: In North Carolina: Alexander, Anson, Cabarrus, Catawba, Cleveland, Gaston, Iredell, Lincoln, Mecklenburg, Rowan, Stanly and Union. In South Carolina: Chester, Chesterfield, Lancaster and York. Step 1- Submit an online nomination: Fill out the form below to submit your nomination to the Charlotte Business Journal. Make sure your company meets the nomination criteria.\n    Step 2- Register with Quantum Workplace: Beginning in early August, you will receive an email from Quantum Workplace that contains a link to access the online employee engagement registration page. Here you will register your company for the survey and receive your company''s organization code and the address of the survey website.', '1-Nov-15', 0, 0, 'Charlotte', 'NC', 'USA', 'US South', '', '', 'Annual', 'Allie Gatlin', 'agatlin@bizjournals.com', '', 'Law Firm; Company; Organization', '', '2013', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/nomination/64771', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte', ''),
(599, 'Charlotte Business Journal', '40 Under 40', 2015, 'The Charlotte Business Journal is recognizing the Charlotte region’s 40 Under 40. These are 40 individuals under the age of 40 who are making major strides in their careers and having a positive impact on their communities.', '1-Dec-15', 0, 0, 'Charlotte', 'NC', 'USA', 'US South', '', '', 'Annual', 'Allie Gatlin', 'agatlin@bizjournals.com', '704-973-1703', 'Individual', 'Age', '2013', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/event/93971', '', ''),
(600, 'Charlotte Business Journal', 'Healthiest Employers of Greater Charlotte Awards', 2016, 'The Charlotte Business Journal''s annual Healthiest Employers of Greater Charlotte Awards program honors local companies with outstanding health and wellness initiatives. We''re looking for organizations that are committed to creating a healthy workplace and making wellness a priority and proactively shaping the health of their employees. Nominate your company today to see how your wellness program measures up to the competition! Company must be located in the Charlotte region. Charlotte region is defined by the following counties: In North Carolina: Alexander, Anson, Cabarrus, Catawba, Cleveland, Gaston, Iredell, Lincoln, Mecklenburg, Rowan, Stanly and Union. In South Carolina: Chester, Chesterfield, Lancaster and York', '11-Mar-16', 0, 0, 'Charlotte', 'NC', 'USA', 'US South', '', 'Recognition: Honorees and winners will be recognized at an awards program and in a special publication of the Charlotte Business Journal on November 2014.\n    Free Survey Overview Report: You will get a free report on your company''s survey results, which ', 'Annual', 'Allie Gatlin', 'agatlin@bizjournals.com', '', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/nomination/79342?ana=et_clt_healthiestnom#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte', ''),
(601, 'Charlotte Business Journal', 'Women in Business Awards', 2016, 'Recognize the successes of professional women in the Charlotte area by submitting a nomination for the 20th Annual Women in Business Achievement Awards program. We''re looking for women from every industry and profession — women who have made a difference in their workplace and are blazing trails for other women.\n\nThe 25 winners and Lifetime Achievement Award winner will be recognized at a special awards celebration on June 16, 2016 and will be profiled in the June 17 publication of the Charlotte Business Journal.', '27-Mar-16', 0, 0, 'Charlotte', 'NC', 'USA', 'US South', '', '', 'Annual', 'Allie Gatlin', 'agatlin@bizjournals.com', '', 'Individual', 'Women', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/nomination/79372#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte', ''),
(602, 'Charlotte Business Journal', 'CFO of the Year Awards', 2016, 'The Charlotte Business Journal''s 2016 CFO of the Year Awards will be given to top local professionals with outstanding performance in their roles as senior financial leaders.\nEligibility:\nNominee must be a Chief Financial Officer or hold an equivalent title at the time of the nomination.\nExecutives who do not carry a CFO designation are eligible as long as they are the top finance executive in the company.\nNominee must have served a minimum period of three years as CFO or equivalent title. This doesn''t require holding the title for 3+ years at the same company, just 3+ years during their career.\nNominee must reside and work in one of the 16 counties in the Charlotte area: The Charlotte area is defined by the following counties: Alexander, Anson, Cabarrus, Catawba, Chester, Chesterfield, Cleveland, Gaston, Iredell, Lancaster, Lincoln, Mecklenburg, Rowan, Stanly, Union and York.', '17-Apr-16', 0, 0, 'Charlotte', 'NC', 'USA', 'US South', '', 'Recognition: Honorees and winners will be recognized at an awards program and in a special publication of the Charlotte Business Journal on November 2014.\n    Free Survey Overview Report: You will get a free report on your company''s survey results, which ', 'Annual', 'Allie Gatlin', 'agatlin@bizjournals.com', '', 'Individual', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/nomination/79482#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte', '');
