(810, 'New York State Bar Association', 'Root/Stimson Award', 0, 'The Root/Stimson Award honors a lawyer who has demonstrated outstanding commitment to community and volunteer service and to the improvement of the justice system. Named for Elihu Root and Henry L. Stimson to honor their commitment to public service, this award is presented to a lawyer admitted to practice in New York state who is actively involved in volunteer community service work. The award recognizes members of the legal profession who have given unstintingly of their time through community service activities. NOTE: The committee is not seeking nominees who have provided pro bono legal services representation. Those nominations should be submitted for consideration to the President''s Committee on Access to Justice which administers the annual pro bono award.', '2-May-16', 0, 1, '', 'NY', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', 'Bridget Donion', 'bdonion@nysba.org', '', 'Individual', '', '2015', 'http://www.nysba.org/CustomTemplates/SecondaryStandard.aspx?id=32366', '', ''),
(811, 'New York State Bar Association', ' Ruth G. Schapiro Memorial Award', 2016, 'To honor a male or female member of the Association who has made a noteworthy contribution to the concerns of women through pro bono services, writing, service to bar associations or community organizations or other such endeavors.   Person must be a member of the NYSBA and must have made a noteworthy contribution to the concerns of women through activities stated above. ', '2-Nov-15', 0, 1, '', 'NY', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', 'Robyn Ryan', 'rryan@nysba.org', '518-487-5560', 'Individual', 'Pro Bono; Women', '2015', 'http://www.nysba.org/CustomTemplates/Content.aspx?id=27257', 'https://www.nysba.org', ''),
(812, 'New York State Bar Association', 'Kay Crawford Murray Award ', 2016, 'To honor women in the profession who recognize the value of diversity in the legal profession and have dedicated their time to advancing the professional development of women attorneys. Future recipients will possess the following characteristics: a distinguished legal career or a rising star in the profession; an active member of bar associations for the purpose of advancing the professional and personal development of women attorneys; an active mentor to women attorneys.    The award was developed and is administered by the Committee on Women\nin the Law. Future recipients will possess the following characteristics:\n(1) a distinguished legal career or a rising\nstar in the profession;\n(2) an active member of one or more\nbar associations for the purpose of\nadvancing the professional and personal\ndevelopment of women attorneys;\n(3) an active mentor to women attorneys;\nand\n(4) a substantial contributor to increasing\nthe value of diversity in the legal\nProfession. ', '2-Nov-15', 0, 1, '', 'NY', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', 'Robyn Ryan', 'rryan@nysba.org', '518-487-5560', 'Individual', 'Women', '2015', 'https://www.nysba.org/CustomTemplates/Content.aspx?id=27256', 'https://www.nysba.org', ''),
(813, 'New York State Bar Association', ' Outstanding Young Lawyer Award ', 2016, 'Each year, the Young Lawyers Section of the New York State\nBar Association honors a young lawyer who has rendered\noutstanding service to both the community and the legal\nprofession. The Outstanding Young Lawyer Award recognizes\nan attorney who has actively practiced less than ten years and has a distinguished record of\ncommitment to the finest traditions of the Bar through public service and professional activities.\nThese activities may include, but are not limited to pro bono service, service to bar associations\nand community organizations, and participation in those activities that enhance the profession\nand benefit the public.\nThe award will be presented at the Young Lawyers Section Executive Committee Meeting during\nthe New York State Bar Association Annual Meeting in January 2016.\nEligibility and Award Criteria\n• Nominees must be admitted to practice in New York State and have practiced less than ten\nyears at the time of nomination. Membership in the NYSBA is not required.\n• Nominees must be involved primarily in the active practice of law as distinguished from\nan attorney who has been primarily engaged in business, or as a legislator, or other holder\nof public office or position, where admission to the Bar is not required.\n• Service in a public service position such as district attorney, assistant district attorney,\nattorney general, assistant attorney general, judgeships, or judicial clerkships will be\nincluded for determining years of practice, but will not be considered community\nor professional service.\n• Members of the New York State Bar Association Young Lawyers Section Executive\nCommittee and past chairpersons of the Section are not eligible for nomination.\n• All submissions require a completed nomination form. Please attach additional sheets,\nif necessary.\n• Letters and a resume supporting the nomination will be considered, if they enhance the\ninformation provided in the nomination form', '6-Nov-15', 0, 1, '', 'NY', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', ' Megan O’Toole', 'motoole@nysba.org', '', 'Individual', 'Years In Practice', '2015', 'https://www.nysba.org/oyl/', 'https://www.nysba.org', ''),
(814, 'New York State Bar Association', 'Award for Attorney Professionalism', 2016, 'To honor a member of the NYSBA for outstanding professionalism, which is defined as dedication to service to clients and a commitment to promoting respect for the legal system in pursuit of justice and the public good, characterized by exemplary ethical conduct, competence, good judgment, integrity and civility   . Attorney professionalism is dedication to service to clients and a commitment to promoting respect for the legal system in pursuit of justice and the public good, characterized by exemplary ethical conduct, competence, good judgment, integrity and civility.\n\nThe Award honors attorneys who evidence the highest attributes of professionalism in the practice of law: attorneys who have labored in “the vineyard” and are especially valued by their clients and their colleagues. Therefore, rather than a lifetime achievement award, this particular honor relates to professionalism in the actual practice of law. Background letters from clients, other attorneys and judges have provided a full picture for the reviewing committee in the past. Your nomination should, as inclusively as possible, specify how the nominee has demonstrated the following attributes:\n\na) Dedication to service to clients and always acting in the best interests of the client;\n\nb) Civility: behaving to all with courtesy, consideration and respect;\n\nc) Exemplary ethical conduct: endeavoring at all times to fulfill the spirit, and not just the requirements, of the NY Rules of Professional Conduct;\n\nd) Competence: keeping abreast of the latest developments in his or her area of practice;\n\ne) Good judgment: providing client service consisting of discerning opinions and advice based upon knowledge, experience, moral as well as legal considerations;\n\nf) Mentoring, educating and assisting other attorneys;\n\ng) Integrity: always exhibiting soundness of character, fidelity, honesty and fairness.\n\n\nPlease keep in mind, in considering your nomination, that there are other awards honoring service to bar associations and pro bono activities. In this Attorney Professionalism Award, the New York State Bar Association seeks to honor a person who exemplifies the highest standards of professionalism in the actual practice of law. ', '16-Nov-15', 0, 1, '', 'NY', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', 'Richard Rifkin ', 'rrifkin@nysba.org', '', 'Individual', '', '2015', 'https://www.nysba.org/AttorneyProfessionalism/', 'https://www.nysba.org', ''),
(815, 'New York State Bar Association', ' Outstanding Young Lawyer Award ', 2016, 'Each year, the Young Lawyers Section of the New York State Bar Association honors a young lawyer who has rendered outstanding service to both the community and the legal\nprofession. The Outstanding Young Lawyer Award recognizes an attorney who has actively practiced less than ten years and has a distinguished record of commitment to the finest traditions of the Bar through public service and professional activities.\nThese activities may include, but are not limited to pro bono service, service to bar associations and community organizations, and participation in those activities that enhance the profession and benefit the public.\nThe award will be presented at the Young Lawyers Section Executive Committee Meeting during the New York State Bar Association Annual Meeting in January 2016.\nEligibility and Award Criteria\n• Nominees must be admitted to practice in New York State and have practiced less than ten years at the time of nomination. Membership in the NYSBA is not required.\n• Nominees must be involved primarily in the active practice of law as distinguished from an attorney who has been primarily engaged in business, or as a legislator, or other holder of public office or position, where admission to the Bar is not required.\n• Service in a public service position such as district attorney, assistant district attorney,\nattorney general, assistant attorney general, judgeships, or judicial clerkships will be\nincluded for determining years of practice, but will not be considered community\nor professional service.\n• Members of the New York State Bar Association Young Lawyers Section Executive\nCommittee and past chairpersons of the Section are not eligible for nomination.\n• All submissions require a completed nomination form. Please attach additional sheets,\nif necessary.\n• Letters and a resume supporting the nomination will be considered, if they enhance the\ninformation provided in the nomination form', '7-Nov-16', 0, 1, '', 'NY', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', ' Megan O’Toole', 'motoole@nysba.org', '', 'Individual', 'Years In Practice', '2015', 'https://www.nysba.org/oyl/', 'https://www.nysba.org', ''),
(816, 'NJBIZ', 'Business of the Year', 2016, 'The NJBIZ Business of the Year awards recognizes the state’s most dynamic businesses and business leaders who share a commitment to professional excellence, business growth and the community. Award Categories:\n- Business of the Year (1-50 employees)\n- Business of the Year (51-100 employees)\n- Business of the Year (101+ employees)\n- Corporate Citizen of the Year\n- Emerging Business of the Year\n\nEligibility:\n- Nominees may not be entered in a category in which they have previously won. After a five year period, companies may re-apply for a category in which they have already won.\n- Nominees may be self-nominated or nominated by someone else.\n- Nominees may only be entered in one category.\n- Nominees may not be members of the judges’ panel or members of the judges’ families.\n- Nominations that do not follow guidelines may be subject to disqualification. \n- Past finalists will be accepted.', '10-Sep-15', 0, 0, '', 'NJ', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', 'Erika Plateroti', 'erikap@njbiz.com', '(732) 246-5713', 'Law Firm; Organization; Company', 'Community or civic', '2015', 'http://www.njbiz.com/section/Business-of-the-Year-Nom', 'http://www.njbiz.com/', 'subscribed'),
(817, 'NJBIZ', 'Best Places to Work', 2016, 'Eligibility\nTo be eligible for consideration, companies must meet the following criteria:\nBe a for-profit or not-for-profit business or government entity\nBe a publicly or privately held business\nHave a facility in the state of New Jersey\nHave a minimum of 15 employees working in the state of New Jersey*\nMust be in business a minimum of 1 year\n*To ensure the credibility of the information, companies with 15-24 employees must have an 80% (or better) response rate to be considered for the list.', '13-Nov-15', 0, 0, '', 'NJ', 'USA', 'US Northeast', '', '', 'Annual', 'Katie Smith', 'KatieS@BestCompaniesGroup.com ', ' (877) 455-2159', 'Law Firm; Organization; Company', 'Community or Civic', '2014', 'http://www.bestplacestoworkinnj.com/index.php?option=com_frontpage&Itemid=1', 'http://www.njbiz.com/', 'subscribed'),
(818, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Business Women First', 2016, 'Presented by the Pittsburgh Business Times, the  BusinessWomen First Awards honor the region''s most influential business women at both for-profits and non-profits. We''re looking for women from every industry and profession; women who''ve made a difference in their communities, blazed a trail for other women and are leaving a mark on the western Pennsylvania business community.\nNominees must be female residents of western Pennsylvania who are employed in the region.\nA nominee should be an established business leader with a strong record of innovation in her field with outstanding performance in her business or non-profit or organization.\nNominations should include as much detail as possible about a nominee''s specific business accomplishments. We''re looking for real tangible results, as in ''She increased the company''s sales last year by 40%, bringing in AOL and Nextel as clients.''\nNominees do not have to be the owners or presidents of their organizations. We do not publicize the name of the person who enters a nomination.\nNominees will be judged on their role as business or non-profit leaders. We''re looking for entrepreneurs and executives whose efforts are molding their workplace and their industry.', '18-Dec-15', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', 'Richard Cerilli', ' rcerilli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3815', 'Individual', 'Women', '2013', '', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(819, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Family Business Awards', 2016, ' Presented by the Pittsburgh Business Times, the 2016 Family Business Awards will honor multi-generational, family-owned businesses in our region for overall excellence, innovation, ethics and philanthropy. Finalists will be selected by an independent panel of judges.\nCompanies who won this award in 2015 are not eligible to participate in 2016.\nFinalists will be announced in advance. Winners will be named at a luncheon during the second week of May of 2016. Finalists and winners will be honored in a special supplement to the Pittsburgh Business Times on May 13, 2016\n.\nAwards will be presented in categories based on employee count.', '12-Feb-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', '', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77472', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(820, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Energy Leadership Awards', 2016, 'The 2016 Energy Leadership Awards honor individuals for outstanding contributions to western Pennsylvania''s energy sector.\n\nWe honor all types of energy leadership  – from energy companies that explore and drill for gas and oil to the attorneys and accountants who supply services to them. While natural gas is clearly a strong focal point of the program, the 2016 Energy Leadership Awards will honor all categories, including natural gas, oil, coal, nuclear, wind and solar. If you work with the energy industry or know a person who does, you should consider entering the 2016 Energy Leadership Awards.\n\nThis is the sixth year for the program, which includes an awards event and a special supplement in May of 2016.\n\nWinners will be announced in May of 2016 at the Energy Gala, a reception honoring the region''s energy leaders.', '19-Feb-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', 'Energy & Natural Resources', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Community or Civic', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77482#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(821, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Fast Trackers', 2016, 'Fast Trackers honors leaders in Pittsburgh''s business and nonprofit communities who are under 40 years old as of June 1, 2016. Winners are selected for their successful efforts to grow a business or nonprofit. Fast Trackers don''t have to be owners, presidents or executive directors of their organizations, but they must have shown to have had a significant impact on the growth, scope or impact of the organization.\nSelf-nominations are encouraged for this program. Individuals who won this award in 2015 are not eligible to participate in 2016. Winners are in a special Business Times supplement and through online coverage.', '11-Mar-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Individual', 'Age', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77502#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(822, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Healthiest Employers in Western Pennsylvania', 2016, 'The 2016 Healthiest Employers in Western Pennsylvania awards program honors companies in Western Pennsylvania for programs developed to improve the health and wellness of employees. To participate, a company representitive must register on this website.', '11-Mar-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', '', '2015', 'http://healthiestemployers.com/portfolio/western-pennsylvania/', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(823, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Fastest Growing Companies', 2016, 'Do you represent one of our region''s fastest-growing companies? You should enter the 2016 Pittsburgh 100.\nTo qualify, companies must be locally owned, for-profit corporations, proprietorships or partnerships. Revenue growth is ranked over a three-year period between 2013 and 2015. Gross revenue in 2013 must be $500,000 or above. Some information, including the percentage of growth between 2013 and 2015, will be included in the Pittsburgh 100 supplement of the Pittsburgh Business Times in August of 2016. Revenue numbers are not published as part of this List, but may be used for and published in other Lists, such as the Largest Regional Private Companies. If you do not want your revenue figures published in any Lists, please contact Ethan Lott, elott@bizjournals.com or 412-208-3823.', '20-May-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77522#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(824, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Best Places to Work', 2016, 'The 2016 Best Places to Work in Western Pennsylvania honors the region''s most outstanding workplaces. Winners are selected based on an online employee survey in June of this year and are honored at an event and in a special supplement. You must have at least 10 employees working in western Pennsylvania to participate. (Anyone with 5 percent or more ownership in the company may not participate in the survey and does not count toward the final employee total.) Companies do not have to be based in western Pennsylvania. Only employees working in the region are included in the survey and results. You''ll be notified in late May, 2016, with instructions on how to sign up for the online survey.', '27-May-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', 'Richard Cerilli', ' rcerilli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3815', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77542#eligibility', 'www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh', ''),
(825, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Women in Energy Awards', 2016, 'The 2016 Health Care Heroes Awards will honor the individuals, companies and organizations in western Pennsylvania for their contributions to improving health care in our region. Awards are presented in seven categories: Community Outreach, Health Care Innovation, Health Care Provider - Physician, Health Care Provider - Nonphysician, Volunteer, Health Care Executive and Lifetime Achievement.The selections are made by an independent panel of judges. Winners and finalists are honored at an event and in a special supplement in September of 2016.\nSelf-nominations are encouraged. The names of the nominators are not publicized at any stage of this program.\nIndividuals who won this award in 2015 are not eligible to participate in 2016.', '27-May-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', 'Energy & Natural Resources', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Individual', 'Women', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77532#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(826, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Healthcare Hero Awards', 2016, 'The 2016 Health Care Heroes Awards will honor the individuals, companies and organizations in western Pennsylvania for their contributions to improving health care in our region. Awards are presented in seven categories: Community Outreach, Health Care Innovation, Health Care Provider - Physician, Health Care Provider - Nonphysician, Volunteer, Health Care Executive and Lifetime Achievement.The selections are made by an independent panel of judges. Winners and finalists are honored at an event and in a special supplement in September of 2016.\nSelf-nominations are encouraged. The names of the nominators are not publicized at any stage of this program.\nIndividuals who won this award in 2015 are not eligible to participate in 2016.', '10-Jun-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', 'Healthcare', '', '', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', '', '2015', 'http://healthiestemployers.com/portfolio/western-pennsylvania/', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(827, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Who''s Who In Energy', 2016, 'With the Pittsburgh region becoming an energy bastion in the east, help us identify the movers and shakers fueling the energy boom in our region.\n\nThis fall, the Pittsburgh Business Times will publish the fourth annual edition of a multistate publication, ''Who''s Who in Energy.''\n\nBusiness journals in five cities - Dallas, Denver, Houston, Pittsburgh and San Antonio - will partner on this undertaking, the result of which will be a listing of some 700 business leaders across sectors and states who are shaping today''s ever-evolving energy market.\n\nThe Pittsburgh Business Times will accept nominations through Aug. 12, 2016. Honorees can work in positions throughout the energy industry, including (but not limited to) finance, law, engineering, renewable, manufacturing, advocacy/education/training and energy companies themselves.\n\nYou can nominate yourself or another outstanding Pittsburgh regional business leader.\n\nThe Business Times will vet all entries and make the final decision on this year''s movers and shakers.\n\nVisit the other business journal sites to nominate individuals in those markets.', '12-Aug-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', 'Energy & Natural Resources', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Individual', 'Commui', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/78082#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(828, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'CFO of the Year', 2016, 'The CFO of the Year Awards honors financial professionals in western Pennsylvania for outstanding performance as corporate financial stewards.\n\nEligibility: Nominees must be Chief Financial Officers or hold equivalent positions in the western Pennsylvania region. Companies do not have to be headquartered in region, but CFO nominees must have home office in the region.\n\nIndividuals who won this award in 2015 are not eligible to participate in 2016.\nAwards\nAwards will be provided in categories. Up to five finalists will be selected in each category. Winners will be announced at the awards ceremony. Categories include:\n• Public\n• Non-Profit\n• Private (three categories based on company size using employee count)\n• Lifetime Achievement (new for 2016)\nRecognition: Finalists and winners will be honored at a dinner awards ceremony in November, 2016 at the Omni William Penn Hotel in downtown Pittsburgh. A special supplement honoring participants will be inserted in the Pittsburgh Business Times later that same week.\nSelection Process: An independent panel of judges, which includes winners of the 2015 CFO of the Year Awards will select winners based on information provided through this online nomination. Only online nominations will be accepted.\nSpecial Notes:\n• Self-nominations account for more than half of all nominations for awards programs presented by the Pittsburgh Business Times. We do not publicize the nominator in any way. Judges are not provided with the names or affiliations of nominators. They review only the answers to the questions from this nomination.\n• This system does not save your nomination. We recommend that you first draft your responses in a Word document in the event you either experience an error message or want to review the nomination in the future. Do not exceed 2,000 characters, including spaces, per field.\nIf you want to nominate someone, but don''t have the information to complete this form\nIf you know of a deserving candidate for this award, but don''t feel you have the necessary information to complete the nomination:\n1. Provide your name and contact information.\n2. Provide the nominee''s name and contact information.\n3. Put ''NA'' in the remaining fields. You''ll be contacted about someone from the Business Times reaching out to the candidate to get the rest of the information.', '19-Aug-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', 'Richard Cerilli', ' rcerilli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3815', 'Individual', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77552#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(829, 'Pittsburgh Business Times', 'Manufacturer of the Year', 2016, 'The 2016 Manufacturer of the Year Awards are given to companies based on information provided in this online nomination form by a panel of independent judges. There are three award categories: Overall, Sustainable and a category that was introduced last year - the Family Business Award.\nNote: Companies who won this award in 2015 are not eligible to participate in 2016.\nOverall\nUp to five finalists and one winner are selected in three overall categories based on employee count (small, medium, large).\nSustainable\nThe sustainable manufacturing award is based on sustainable products or processes at a manufacturing facility in western Pennsylvania. Up to five finalists and one winner are selected in the sustainable category.\n\nPremo J. Pappafava Family Business Award\nThis award will recognize multi-generational, family-owned manufacturers for overall excellence, innovation, ethics and philanthropy. One winner is selected in this category.\n\nSelf-nominations are encouraged for this program. Nearly all finalists and winners from prior years were the result of nominations by someone at the company.\n\nYou may apply for both the overall or sustainable award, or for only the sustainable or overall category.\n\nThis nominating system does not save your work. We suggest you provide the narratives to the questions on this form in a Word document, then copy them into the answer fields.', '2-Sep-16', 0, 0, 'Pittsburgh', 'PA', 'USA', 'US Mid-Atlantic', '', '', 'Annual', ' Rick Vaccarelli', 'rvaccarelli@bizjournals.com', '412-208-3813', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/nomination/77562#eligibility', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/', ''),
(830, 'Power Magazine', 'Power Awards - Plant of the Year', 2016, 'For over four decades, POWER magazine has honored the top performers in the electricity-generating industry with annual power plant awards. If your plant has distinguished itself by innovative design or engineering upgrades, producing power more reliably or economically than comparable plants, or demonstrating a new generation or environmental controls technology, don’t miss the opportunity to see your plant profiled in POWER. We also offer an award for a noteworthy smart grid project and plant water-related project.\n\nAward winners will be selected by the editors of POWER based on nominations submitted by you and your industry peers—suppliers, designers, constructors, and operators of power plants. Don’t be shy about nominating your plant; most of our past winners were nominated by plant staff. If your project is selected as an award finalist, a POWER editor will contact you to develop an article that will be published in POWER to inform the rest of the industry of your achievement. Additionally, all winners will be mailed an award that displays their project’s name on a custom POWER cover. Plant of the Year\n\nThe Plant of the Year award is given to a power plant that leads our industry in the successful deployment of advanced technology and maximizing efficiency while minimizing environmental impact. Historically, this award has been presented to a plant that entered commercial service within the past one to two years. The Plant of the Year will be profiled in the August issue of POWER', '29-Apr-16', 0, 0, '', '', 'USA', '', 'Energy & Natural Resources', 'Power;', 'Annual', '', 'awards@powermag.com', '', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.powermag.com/', 'http://www.powermag.com/power-awards/', ''),
(831, 'Power Magazine', 'Power Awards - Reinvention Award (previously Marmaduke Award)', 2016, 'For over four decades, POWER magazine has honored the top performers in the electricity-generating industry with annual power plant awards. If your plant has distinguished itself by innovative design or engineering upgrades, producing power more reliably or economically than comparable plants, or demonstrating a new generation or environmental controls technology, don’t miss the opportunity to see your plant profiled in POWER. We also offer an award for a noteworthy smart grid project and plant water-related project.\n\nAward winners will be selected by the editors of POWER based on nominations submitted by you and your industry peers—suppliers, designers, constructors, and operators of power plants. Don’t be shy about nominating your plant; most of our past winners were nominated by plant staff. If your project is selected as an award finalist, a POWER editor will contact you to develop an article that will be published in POWER to inform the rest of the industry of your achievement. Additionally, all winners will be mailed an award that displays their project’s name on a custom POWER cover. Reinvention Award (previously Marmaduke Award)\n\nThe Reinvention Award recognizes excellence in creative problem-solving that gives a power plant of any type a new life or a new role. Prior winners include an operating combined cycle plant that was moved from one multi-unit plant to another multi-unit plant, a coal-fired plant that was repowered with a circulating fluidized bed (CFB) boiler burning wood, and a district heating plant that was repowered with new, high-efficiency gas turbines. The Reinvention Award winner will be profiled in the August issue of POWER.', '29-Apr-16', 0, 0, '', '', 'USA', '', 'Energy & Natural Resources', 'Power;', 'Annual', '', 'awards@powermag.com', '', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.powermag.com/', 'http://www.powermag.com/power-awards/', ''),
(832, 'Power Magazine', 'Power Awards - Smart Grid Award', 2016, 'For over four decades, POWER magazine has honored the top performers in the electricity-generating industry with annual power plant awards. If your plant has distinguished itself by innovative design or engineering upgrades, producing power more reliably or economically than comparable plants, or demonstrating a new generation or environmental controls technology, don’t miss the opportunity to see your plant profiled in POWER. We also offer an award for a noteworthy smart grid project and plant water-related project.\n\nAward winners will be selected by the editors of POWER based on nominations submitted by you and your industry peers—suppliers, designers, constructors, and operators of power plants. Don’t be shy about nominating your plant; most of our past winners were nominated by plant staff. If your project is selected as an award finalist, a POWER editor will contact you to develop an article that will be published in POWER to inform the rest of the industry of your achievement. Additionally, all winners will be mailed an award that displays their project’s name on a custom POWER cover. Smart Grid Award\n\n2011 was the inaugural year for the POWER Smart Grid Award. Although the magazine has traditionally focused on the supply end of the power industry, the business and technology of power generation is becoming increasingly affected by smart grid developments that touch the entire power supply and delivery chain. This award recognizes an outstanding smart grid project, anywhere in the world, of any scale, that demonstrates the benefits of new data-rich technologies to power generators, distribution utilities, and customers. Specifically, we are looking for nominations of projects that are:\n\nUpstream of smart meters and home energy management or automation devices, so no automated meter reading or advanced metering infrastructure projects, please—unless they are just a portion of a more comprehensive smart grid project that has several other non-end-user components.\nClearly “smart”—that integrate information and communications technology-assisted components that represent more than maintenance-level improvement.\nSetting a new standard for quality and results. Being the “first” or “largest” or “cheapest” of a given type of project will be noted but will not be the weightiest criterion. Whether large or small, the winning project will need to demonstrate achievement in technology and service that is worthy of being considered a best practice.\nAble to demonstrate material results from at least six months of operation prior to the nomination deadline. No planned or in-progress projects, please. (We realize that all true smart grid projects are works in progress, but we are looking for projects with a defined scope that have been completed, monitored, and reported on.) For example, specify costs saved by end users, outages averted that would not previously have been avoided, dispatchable or controllable small-scale distributed generation resources added to the grid in such a way that they strengthen the grid rather than destabilize it, or some other metric(s) that illustrate the substantive benefits enjoyed by one or (preferably) more grid stakeholders.', '29-Apr-16', 0, 0, '', '', 'USA', '', 'Energy & Natural Resources', 'Power;', 'Annual', '', 'awards@powermag.com', '', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.powermag.com/', 'http://www.powermag.com/power-awards/', ''),
(833, 'Power Magazine', 'Power Awards - Top Plants', 2016, 'For over four decades, POWER magazine has honored the top performers in the electricity-generating industry with annual power plant awards. If your plant has distinguished itself by innovative design or engineering upgrades, producing power more reliably or economically than comparable plants, or demonstrating a new generation or environmental controls technology, don’t miss the opportunity to see your plant profiled in POWER. We also offer an award for a noteworthy smart grid project and plant water-related project.\n\nAward winners will be selected by the editors of POWER based on nominations submitted by you and your industry peers—suppliers, designers, constructors, and operators of power plants. Don’t be shy about nominating your plant; most of our past winners were nominated by plant staff. If your project is selected as an award finalist, a POWER editor will contact you to develop an article that will be published in POWER to inform the rest of the industry of your achievement. Additionally, all winners will be mailed an award that displays their project’s name on a custom POWER cover. Top Plants\n\nTop Plant winners are profiled annually in these issues of POWER:\n\nNatural gas-fired projects in September\nCoal-fired projects in October\nNuclear projects in November\nRenewable projects in December\nTop Plants are interesting, important, innovative projects. Many Top Plants are recently commissioned facilities that exhibit some unique design or technology that will be of general interest to the power industry. They also can include plants that have distinguished themselves as industry leaders for significant improvements made to their equipment, operations, staffing, or operating record to emerge from an “also ran” to top of the class in performance.', '29-Apr-16', 0, 0, '', '', 'USA', '', 'Energy & Natural Resources', 'Power;', 'Annual', '', 'awards@powermag.com', '', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.powermag.com/', 'http://www.powermag.com/power-awards/', ''),
(834, 'Power Magazine', 'Power Awards - Water Award', 2016, 'For over four decades, POWER magazine has honored the top performers in the electricity-generating industry with annual power plant awards. If your plant has distinguished itself by innovative design or engineering upgrades, producing power more reliably or economically than comparable plants, or demonstrating a new generation or environmental controls technology, don’t miss the opportunity to see your plant profiled in POWER. We also offer an award for a noteworthy smart grid project and plant water-related project.\n\nAward winners will be selected by the editors of POWER based on nominations submitted by you and your industry peers—suppliers, designers, constructors, and operators of power plants. Don’t be shy about nominating your plant; most of our past winners were nominated by plant staff. If your project is selected as an award finalist, a POWER editor will contact you to develop an article that will be published in POWER to inform the rest of the industry of your achievement. Additionally, all winners will be mailed an award that displays their project’s name on a custom POWER cover. Water Award\n\nIntroduced in 2014, the Water Award goes to a water-related project at a power plant anywhere in the world that demonstrates leadership in the management of water and/or wastewater streams. Winning projects will have successfully implemented innovative, leading-edge approaches to water stewardship, water quality, water availability, or wastewater-handling issues. Although technology may be involved, the award is not specifically for a new commercially available technology. Rather, the award recognizes creative problem-solving that results in water management strategies that may serve as models for other plants. ''|29-Apr-16|0|0|||USA''', '', 0, 0, 'Annual', '', 'awards@powermag.com', '', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.powermag.com/', 'http://www.powermag.com/power-awards/', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(835, 'San Antonia Business Journal', 'Best Places to Work', 2016, 'The San Antonio Business Journal is seeking nominations for its Best Places to Work awards. To nominate, companies must complete this form below and register for their employees to complete an electronic survey. The deadline to submit nominations is March 25.', '25-Mar-16', 0, 0, 'San Antonio', 'Texas', 'USA', 'US South', '', '', 'Annual', 'Susan Saporito', 'bestplacessa@bizjournals.com', '477-0845', 'Law Firm; Company; Organization', 'Community or Civic', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/sanantonio/nomination', '', ''),
(836, 'San Antonia Business Journal', 'Outstanding Lawyer Awards', 2016, 'The San Antonio Business Journal''s Outstanding Lawyer Awards recognize lawyers in our community who are making a difference in their organizations, the legal industry and the community.\n\nNominees must be practicing lawyers who have passed the Texas Bar exam and are current on continuing professional education requirements.\nThe nominee’s home office must be in the San Antonio area.\n ', '10-Jun-16', 0, 1, 'San Antonio', 'Texas', 'USA', 'US South', '', '', 'Annual', '', '', '', 'Individual', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/sanantonio/nomination', '', ''),
(837, 'San Antonio Business Journal', 'Residential Real Estate Awards', 2016, 'The San Antonio Business Journal is seeking nominations for the Top Residential Real Agents in the following categories: Luxury Real Estate Agents, Luxury Real Estate Teams, Individual Agents, Residential Real Estate Teams, and Farm & Ranch Agents', '25-Feb-16', 0, 0, 'San Antonio', 'Texas', 'USA', 'US South', 'Real Estate', '', 'Annual', '', '', '', 'Individual', '', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/sanantonio/nomination', '', ''),
(838, 'San Antonio Business Journal', 'Best in Commercial Real Estate - Heavy Hitters', 2016, 'The San Antonio Business Journal invites you to nominate San Antonio-based brokers for its 2016 Commercial Real EstateHeavy Hitters Awards. Nominated brokers must be involved in commercial real estate transactions in Bexar, Comal, Guadalupe, Kendall, Wilson, Atascosa, Bandera or Medina county. And sales figures must reflect only transactions in that eight-county area.', '1-Apr-16', 0, 0, 'San Antonio', 'Texas', 'USA', 'US', 'Real Estate', '', 'Annual', '', '', '', 'Individual', '', '', '', '', ''),
(839, 'San Antonio Business Journal', 'Women''s Leadership Awards', 2016, '', '24-Jun-16', 0, 0, 'San Antonio', 'Texas', 'USA', 'US South', '', '', 'Annual', 'Mary Jonas', 'mjonas@bizjournals.com', '210-477-0854.', 'Individual', 'Women', '2015', 'http://www.bizjournals.com/sanantonio/nomination', '', ''),
(840, 'The Lawyer', 'Barrister of the Year', 2016, 'The entry form will ask you for:\nFull details of one benchmark case, illustrating how the individual barrister’s contribution made a significant difference to the outcome, including details of other parties / instructing groups\nInformation relating to previous career history including:\nKey cases\nInitiatives undertaken outside of the law\nSupporting testimony from Private Practice colleagues', '4-Mar-16', 0, 1, '', '', '', 'Europe', '', '', 'Annual', 'Sarah Hetherington', 'sarah.hetherington@centaurmedia.com', '4020 7970 4532', 'Individual', '', '', '', '', ''),
(841, 'The Lawyer', 'Boutique Firm of the Year', 2016, 'This category is open to specialist or regional firms from across the UK which focus primarily on one practice area; entries should cover work undertaken and progress made over the course of the year from April 2015 to the present day. \nThe entry form will ask you for:\nEvidence of:\nStrategic vision and strong leadership\nStrong financial management and growth\nInnovation in client service delivery \nInnovation in pricing\nExcellent talent management and workplace development\nKey clients\nSignificant client wins and feedback\nRecent hires and investment\nLeadership team (including biographies)\nYou will also be asked to provide details of up to three cases or transactions which demonstrate:\nExcellence in the firm’s chosen field\nDepth and breadth of expertise\nCommercial strength\nMarket share and evidence of both growth and retention within their client list\nLegal and/or entrepreneurial innovation\nEvidence of market leading strategy', '4-Mar-16', 0, 1, '', '', '', 'Europe', '', '', 'Annual', 'Sarah Hetherington', 'sarah.hetherington@centaurmedia.com', '4020 7970 4532', 'Law Firm', '', '', '', '', ''),
(842, 'The Lawyer', 'Chambers of the Year', 2016, 'The entry form will ask you for:\nDetails of up to five cases which demonstrate:\nDepth and breadth of quality of work undertaken\nExpertise within a specific area(s)\nGrowth and response to market shifts\nInnovative management and clerking\nYou will also be asked to provide details of: \nYear on year growth in business activity\nFinancial performance\nClearly identifiable strategy\nInnovation in pricing and service delivery\nOutcomes and precedents set', '4-Mar-16', 0, 1, '', '', '', 'Europe', '', '', 'Annual', 'Sarah Hetherington', 'sarah.hetherington@centaurmedia.com', '4020 7970 4532', 'Law Firm; Legal Department; Individual', '', '', '', '', ''),
(843, 'The Lawyer', 'Client Partner of the Year', 2016, 'This year The Lawyer will be going out to its top in-house contacts to gather nominations for Client Partner of the Year; these nominations will be supplemented by information taken from our research portal The Lawyer Market Intelligence.\nFactors taken into account will include:\nSignificant work undertaken by the Partner\nEvidence of innovation and problem solving skills demonstrated by the Partner\nThe Partner’s understanding of the client’s business, company culture and sector\nHow well embedded into the client company the Partner has become, and the levels of interaction between the Partner and senior business executives\nIf you would like to make any recommendations to the panel regarding who should be nominated, please email the following items to sarah.hetherington@centaurmedia.com:\nYour name and contact details\nName and contact details (where possible) of the nominee\n300 word statement (max) detailing why this person should win, taking into account the above factors', '4-Mar-16', 0, 1, '', '', '', 'Europe', '', '', 'Annual', 'Sarah Hetherington', 'sarah.hetherington@centaurmedia.com', '4020 7970 4532', 'Company; Organization; Law Firm', '', '', '', '', ''),
(844, 'The Lawyer', 'Competition Team of the Year', 2016, 'Entries into this category should focus on one standout matter from 1st April 2015 until the present time.\nThe entry form will ask you for:\nFull details of the chosen deal including:\nMarket context\nHistory of client relationship\nHistory of representation – did the representation change?\nTechnical innovation\nInnovation in client service\nInnovation in pricing\nMeasurable outcomes\nA list of all major parties (individuals and firms) involved in the deal, including (where appropriate) key advisers, associates, partners, barristers and in-house counsel.\nSupporting evidence of the team’s performance over the year, including details of:\nInnovation in pricing and service delivery\nClient wins\nFinancial performance\nOutcomes – what does your work mean to the clients you serve\nPrecedents set for contentious work\n\nMultiple entries from one firm are acceptable.   ', '4-Mar-16', 0, 1, '', '', '', 'Europe', 'Antitrust', '', 'Annual', 'Sarah Hetherington', 'sarah.hetherington@centaurmedia.com', '4020 7970 4532', 'Law Firm; Legal Department', '', '', '', '', ''),
(845, 'The Lawyer', 'Corporate Team of the Year', 2016, 'Entries into this category should focus on one standout transaction from 1st April 2015 until the present time.\nThis category is open to transactional teams. We are looking for excellence in one of the following fields: IPO’s (main list or AIM), public M&A, private equity or corporate reorganisations. Entries are welcomed from both domestic and cross-border work. \n\nThe entry form will ask you for:\n\nFull details of the chosen deal including:\nMarket context\nHistory of client relationship\nHistory of representation – did the representation change?\nTechnical innovation\nInnovation in client service\nInnovation in pricing\nMeasurable outcomes\n\nEvidence of what makes this deal truly unique and challenging\n\nA list of all major parties (individuals and firms) involved in the deal, including (where appropriate) key advisers, associates, partners, barristers and in-house counsel.\n\nSupporting evidence of the team’s performance over the year, including details of:\nInnovation in pricing and service delivery\nClient wins\nFinancial performance\nOutcomes – what does your work mean to the clients you serve\nPrecedents set\n\nMultiple entries from one firm are acceptable.', '4-Mar-16', 0, 1, '', '', '', 'Europe', 'Corporate', '', 'Annual', 'Sarah Hetherington', 'sarah.hetherington@centaurmedia.com', '4020 7970 4532', 'Law Firm; Legal Department', '', '', '', '', '');
